Enums from the beginning
1. What problem do enums solve?
You often need a variable that can only be one of a few fixed choices, not any number.
Example: A traffic light is only red, yellow, or green — not 7 or -3.
You could use integers:
0 = red, 1 = yellow, 2 = green
But then nothing stops you from writing color = 99 by mistake. Enums exist so the language knows “only these names are valid.”

2. What is a “classic” / “old” enum?
In C and older C++, you wrote:
enum Color { Red, Yellow, Green };
Here:
• Red, Yellow, Green are constants.
• Traditionally, Red is really an int under the hood (often 0, 1, 2…).
• The names Red, Yellow, Green are dumped into the same namespace as your other code (they are not tucked inside Color).
So you use it like:
Color c = Red;
int x = c;      // allowed: c silently becomes an int
c = 2;          // often allowed or easy to do by mistake (compiler may warn)
That’s what people mean by “old enum” or unscoped enum: the original C-style rule set.

3. What is “int conversion” here?
Conversion means: the value is treated as a normal integer without you asking.
With old enum:
• Storing the enum in an int → usually allowed automatically.
• Sometimes mixing raw numbers and enum → too easy; bugs hide.
So “int conversion” = the enum value silently behaves like an integer, which was convenient but unsafe (wrong numbers, mixing unrelated enums, etc.).

4. What does enum class do differently?
enum class (C++11) adds two big rules:
A) Scoped names
You must write Color::Red, not plain Red.
So Red doesn’t collide with another Red from a different enum or a variable name. Everything lives under Color.
B) No silent conversion to int
enum class Color { Red, Yellow, Green };

Color c = Color::Red;
int x = c;           // ERROR in C++ — no automatic int conversion
int x = static_cast<int>(c);  // OK — you explicitly said "treat as int"
So enum class stops the accidental “it’s just an int” behavior. If you really need a number, you say so with static_cast.
You also can’t usually assign a random integer to Color without a cast — again, fewer mistakes.

5. Side‑by‑side intuition
Idea	Old enum	enum class
How you name values	Red	Color::Red
Acts like int?	Very easily (implicit)	No (unless you cast)
Name clashes	Easier	Harder

6. One sentence each
• Old enum: “Give names to small integers; names leak into scope and often mix with int.”
• Int conversion: “The value is automatically used as a normal integer without extra syntax.”
• enum class: “Names live under the enum type, and the type is not silently an int — safer and clearer.”

7. Tiny full example
// Old style (simplified behavior)
enum OldColor { OldRed, OldGreen };
int a = OldRed;     // works: OldRed is int-like

// C++11 scoped enum
enum class NewColor { Red, Green };
NewColor c = NewColor::Red;
// int b = c;       // error — good!
int b = static_cast<int>(c);  // explicit: you meant it
That’s the whole story from zero: why enums exist, what old enum did, what int conversion meant, and what enum class fixes.



